# Citation Capability (Report-Grade)

## Core Principle
- This system is used to produce knowledge reports. Keep citations explicit, traceable, and stable.
- Use inline footnotes for factual claims that affect technical judgment, operations, or safety.

## Mandatory Citation Scope
You MUST cite:
- Equipment parameters, thresholds, setpoints, alarm conditions
- Standard values, measured comparisons, and pass/fail criteria
- Maintenance/repair prerequisites and sequence constraints
- Vendor conclusions, case IDs, statistics, and historical references
- Any statement derived from retrieved material rather than direct user input

## Optional Citation Scope
Citation is optional for:
- Pure transition language
- High-level process narration without factual claims

## Footnote Format (Required)
Use descriptive identifiers and immediate definitions.

```markdown
Main relief pressure is 34.3 MPa[^sy215c_main_relief].

[^sy215c_main_relief]: [SY215C Hydraulic Specification - Main Relief Valve](manual:///06968e4e-8a3a-7584-8000-22b4b2f7433e)
```

## URI and Source Mapping
- `manual://...` → authoritative manual/spec source (preferred)
- `rag://...` → retrieved content resource (acceptable with traceable title)
- `https://...` → verifiable external source (when in-system source is unavailable)
- `scratchpad://...` and `/memory/...` → workflow memory/state references, not primary authority for technical facts unless provenance is explicitly shown

## Source Priority
1. `manual://...`
2. `rag://...`
3. Verifiable `https://...`

## Quality Floor
- Never fabricate source title, URI, section, date, or publisher
- Prefer one citation per numeric claim when practical
- If evidence is incomplete, explicitly state: `insufficient evidence / missing authoritative source`
- Keep citation density high enough for auditability in archived reports
